{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17605616","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17605616"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:03:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:03:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15867"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15867","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15867"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.16,0.66,0.08,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8558"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63130"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8558","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8558"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15867"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48581"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"8637"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20528"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20615"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63130","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/63130"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe respiratory system develops from endodermal tissue during embryological development.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the initial development of the respiratory system?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Outgrowth from dorsal midgut during week six","Outgrowth from dorsal foregut during week four","Outgrowth from ventral foregut during week four","Outgrowth from ventral hindgut during week eight","Outgrowth from ventral midgut during week six"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe respiratory system develops as an \u003Cstrong\u003Eoutgrowth from the ventral foregut\u003C/strong\u003E during the fourth week of embryological development. This outgrowth, called the respiratory diverticulum or lung bud, will eventually form the larynx, trachea, bronchi, and lungs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options represent common misconceptions:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDorsal midgut\u003C/strong\u003E: The midgut gives rise to portions of the small and large intestine\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDorsal foregut\u003C/strong\u003E: This region gives rise to parts of the gastrointestinal tract\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVentral hindgut\u003C/strong\u003E: This contributes to the distal portion of the digestive tract\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVentral midgut\u003C/strong\u003E: The midgut develops into portions of the small and large intestine\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe respiratory diverticulum is separated from the oesophagus by the tracheo-oesophageal septum, which grows in a cranial-to-caudal direction, dividing the foregut into an anterior respiratory tube and a posterior digestive tube.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The respiratory diverticulum forms during week four of development as an outgrowth of the ventral foregut.","The respiratory diverticulum gives rise to the larynx, trachea, bronchi, and lungs.","The tracheo-oesophageal septum divides the foregut into anterior respiratory and posterior digestive tubes."],"references":["Sadler TW. Langman\u0027s Medical Embryology: Wolters Kluwer; 2015."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48581"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15867"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"da